75-76. Note that by dropping the cons. with serunt for the moment this most frightful of all the portenta following the death of Caesar is, as it were, set off by itself and thus made more prominent. References to this portent are numerous, cp. Pliny, 2, 98, ‘fiunt prodigiosi et longiores solis defectuus, qualis occiso dictatore Caesare et Antoniano bello totius paene anni pallore continuo.’ Plutarch, Caes. 68, also says that the sun was pale and ghastly for the entire year and gave out so little light and heat that the crops did not ripen at all. C. 4, 4, 14). See also Ovid, Met. 15, 7853 Verg.
